post_text:
USDA provides immediate, short-term support for families by offering free meals for all children enrolled in North Butler Schools. This allows North Butler to offer meals to all enrolled children at no charge this fall to minimize the challenges of meal service during a pandemic. No family should have to worry about their child missing out on healthy school breakfast or lunch. This program will continue until December 31st or when USDA ends the funding. Any seconds, a la Carte items, or snack milk will still be charged to student accounts.

To sign up to be on the weekly delivery list please email Kim.marshall@northbutler.org with the following information: 1. Students name; 2. Hybrid or remote; 3. Address for meals to be delivered to.

You must be signed up by Monday at 8:00 AM to start receiving meals that week. Meals will be delivered to the front door.

REMINDER: Required Stopping for School Buses

Approaching the bus from the rear: When you see flashing red or amber warning lights, you are not permitted to pass the school bus and should be prepared to stop. Stop behind the school bus when the school bus stops and the stop arm is extended. Stop no closer than 15 feet from the rear of the bus, and remain stopped until the stop arm is retracted and school bus starts moving again. Proceed with caution.

Meeting the bus from the front: When you see amber warning lights flashing you must slow your vehicle to no more than 20 mph and be prepared to stop. Stop in front of the school bus when the school bus stops and its stop arm is extended. Remain stopped until the stop arm is retracted. Proceed with caution.

2020-2021 Registration for North Butler Schools

There are two options for registration for North Butler Schools. Due to Covid-19, it is strongly recommended to use the Infinite Campus to complete your registration online this year.

1. An online registration option is available at this link: https://bit.ly/NBRegistration20-21.

2. If you need assistance with registration, appointments can be made for in-person assistance on August 10th from 11:00 a.m. to 7:00 p.m. at North Butler Jr/Sr High in Greene. To make an appointment, call the NB Elementary at 319-267-2212 or NB Jr/Sr High at 641-816-5631 beginning on August 3rd between 8 a.m. and 4 p.m.

post_text:
Joel Foster <joel.foster@northbutler.org>
12:09 PM (0 minutes ago)
to All

North Butler School District Patrons:



This morning Governor Reynolds has given us new guidance on returning to school. Please be advised, as we have said all along, that this is a very fluid situation.



On Monday, July 20th we have a webinar with the Iowa Department of Education to get clarification on what this means to North Butler Schools.



As soon as we have a clear idea of what this means for us as we move forward we will release a statement to the staff and public of where we go from here.



I cannot tell you how much we appreciate your patience as we move forward.

Thank you for your understanding,



Joel Foster, Superintendent

post_text: North Butler Jr/Sr High is conducting a local needs assessment regarding our Career and Technical (CTE) programs. The programs at North Butler include business, industrial technology, family and consumer sciences, and Ag. Any parent of a student in grades 9-12 during the 2019-2020 school year is eligible to take the survey. Please help us determine future needs by completing the survey at the link below. There was an error with the survey when it was first sent out via email, but this has been fixed now. Thank you for your help.

post_text:
JH/HS locker items are ready for drive-by pickup at the following dates and times:

Tuesday, May 5th - 5:00 p.m. - 7:00 p.m.
Wednesday, May 6th - Noon. - 2:00 p.m.
Thursday, May 7th - 5:00 p.m. - 7:00 p.m.

A parent or student may pick up items at these times by pulling up to the main doors. A staff member will bring the items out to your car. For safety reasons, parents and students will not be admitted into the building during these times.

Textbooks, library books, uniforms, and other school-issued items should be returned at these times. You may give these items to the staff member at the drive-by pickup event. Laptops do not need to be returned at this time so that they can be utilized for Zoom sessions.

Waterloo Community School District
March 23 at 5:52 PM Â·

You can watch the northern lights tonight via live stream! The live cam is located at the Churchill Northern Studies Center in Manitoba, Canada. Since the cam is situated directly under the aurora oval, youâ€™ll see amazing views of emerald green curtains of lights dancing in the arctic sky. Although the northern lights occur year-round, according to Explore.org, late winter and early spring are the best seasons to see the lights. So nowâ€™s the perfect time to watch the live stream. Tune in during the darkest hours of the night, which are generally from 10 p.m. to 4 a.m. EDT. Visit Explore.org to tune in.

North Butler Lunch Ladies
March 19 at 1:32 PM Â·

Starting Monday March 23,2020 North Butler schools will be offering free sack lunches to children ages 1-18. From 11:30 to 12:30 p.m.

To pick up lunches from the Allison site please drive through the school parking lot, entering by the pool and drive up to the multi purpose doors. Open your vehicle window and tell the attendant how many sack lunches you need for Kids. These will be brought to your vehicle, and you may take them and go.

To pick up lunches from the Greene building please pull up in front of the building (office side) and roll down a window and let the attendant know how many lunches you need for children. These will be brought to your car and you may take them and go.

Please watch your email for a google form to fill out if you need help getting lunches to your students.

Additional sites may be added if needed, Including rural delivery. If you need lunches email: kim.marshall@northbutler.org

post_text: The North Butler board of education will be meeting Wednesday (meeting was posted) to discuss several items that need to be dealt with in regards to the closure of schools. One of the topics is how we deal with staff pay during this time. We would ask all staff to be patient, as certified staff must be paid during this time by law, and we will be discussing hourly staff and how to address those employees. We recognize that this is an event that is beyond the control of all involved. We will notify staff by email following the meeting how we are going to proceed.

We would ask all staff to be patient, as certified staff must be paid during this time by law, and we will be discussing hourly staff and how to address those employees. We recognize that this is an event that is beyond the control of all involved. We will notify staff by email following the meeting how we are going to proceed.

March 16, 2020

RE School Closure

In accordance with the recommendation from Governor Reynolds, North Butler Community Schools will close through Sunday April 12th at this time. All classes, activities, and practices are either cancelled or postponed during the closure. According to information that we have received, this closure could be extended prior to that date.

The administrative team is meeting regularly to discuss how we address the educational needs of our students, and the board will be meeting later in the week to make decisions for moving forward based upon the information that we have.

We are also working on making a meal program available at both sites. The details will be released soon.

We greatly appreciate your patience with our approach, as the information that we receive is ever changing. We will do our best to keep the community abreast of our next steps as decisions are made moving forward.

Stay safe,

Joel Foster, Superintendent

post_text:
COVID-19 UPDATE

We wanted to update you as we continue to monitor the Covid-19 situation. At this time, the Centers for Disease Control is advising school districts, like ours, located in areas where the outbreak is not currently significant to hold off on short-term closures as that may only exacerbate the spread to vulnerable/older adults the children would then be around. At the point where the outbreak may be more pervasive locally, we will consider alternative plans.

At this time we have decided to cancel any non-instructional/non-essential athletics and activities scheduled beginning Saturday, March 14 through Sunday, March 22 to help decrease the number of contacts for students and adults. This includes after school clubs, after school activities, all games/meets, practices, open weight rooms/gyms, any off-site practices or gatherings and any fine arts concerts, plays practices, and/or programs during that time period.

Thank you for your patience and understandingâ€“have a safe and healthy Spring Break!

February Student Artists of the Month:
_______________________________________________________________

Artist: Ann Shafer

Grade: 9

Title of Artwork: Love the Sun

Artist Statement: I was getting tired of winter, so I wanted to do something about spring. The work is a couple of birds watching the sun rise make a rainbow effect. I got the idea from a friend for the rainbow. I figured the birds could be in love, and they could love the sun. I had never done a piece working with more than one canvas. It was a little challenging but fun.

_______________________________________________________________

Artist: Madison Ralls

Grade: 10

Title of Artwork: Summer

Artist Statement: I drew an ice cream cone from a photo I took this summer. I wanted to draw this because it reminds me of one of my favorite memories with my best friends. I was surprised that it turned out good, because when I started I didnâ€™t think I would be able to draw the ice cream well.

The North Butler County Shooting Club will hold a sign up/information session for students in Grades 7-12 in the North Butler/Clarksville School Districtâ€™s on Sunday March 1st, 2020, at 5:30 PM in the North Butler Elementary cafeteria in Allison. In order for this activity to take place, we need some adults to step up and take the reins of the program. Even though some of the leg work and planning has been accomplished, those of us that have been involved do not have the time to set aside to be more involved and will need to turn it over to others. At this time there is still a need for coaches in order to move forward, but the signup needs to take place in order to participate in the spring season, which begins in March.

Please note that this will be a club activity, not a school activity, and that there will be some costs involved. The schools will support the activity and Varsity letters would be given.

Practices would take place at the Clarksville Sportsmanâ€™s Club Near the ethanol plant on Highway 3, times and dates will be set once/if a coach is in place.

post_text:
JUSTINE
North Butler's January Student Artist of the Month

Artist: Justine Hussey

Grade: 12

Title of Artwork: Tree of Memories

Artist Statement: I chose to title this artwork Tree of Memories because the original idea for the tree was that you would be able to hang meaningful things off the branches. I wanted to create something that could have special meaning. The tree with the swing is supposed to symbolize childhood. Then the things hanging off the tree could be in memory of someone or it could symbolize an event that meant a lot to you. Working with clay in a sculptural sense was new to me and a bit challenging. Iâ€™m not used to working with clay, so trying to get it to do what I wanted to was tough. The branches didnâ€™t want to stay in place and things kept breaking. I like how it turned out, though. I so have a few ideas inspired by this artwork, but Iâ€™m not sure if I want to pursue them.

Title of Artwork: Anatomical Dummy No. 1 (Little Man)

Artist Statement: I used clay, glaze, and tempera paint, to create my Little Man. I was inspired by my own interests in art, as well as the anatomical models made around the 1600-1800s. It was challenging to sculpt and fit his organs correctly in his belly. After making my anatomical model, I was inspired to make more model figures following separate themes. I wouldnâ€™t mind trying out different faces and color combinations.

post_text:
Gently Used Books Needed for NBE Book Swap

NBE's upcoming family literacy event, "You Will Do Great Things!" will feature a book swap. Each child in attendance will be able to take a book home with them. To help ensure every child gets a book, children and community members are invited to bring in gently used books, appropriate for readers preschool - sixth grade, to North Butler Elementary School, located at 513 Birch Street in Allison, Iowa. Books are welcome any time. Those who opt to donate books, are reminded to label them with a note explaining they are for the book swap. Any extra books will be shared in NBE's little outdoor library which is located near the main entrance. This family literacy event will take place at North Butler Elementary School from 4:00 PM - 5:30 PM on February 12, 2020.

post_text:
"You Will Do Great Things!" Family Literacy Event Planned for February 12th, 2020 at North Butler Elementary School

North Butler Elementary School staff is making plans for a family literacy event inspired by Jennifer K. Schmitt's book, "You Will Do Great Things." The author will be on hand for a book signing. Guests will have the opportunity to visit interest areas which will promote literacy through reading, music, creative movement, writing, art, and design.

As in the featured book, students will be encouraged to focus on what they can do, rather than what they can't do. They will be encouraged to grow their talents and use them to do great things. The event will take place from 4:00 PM - 5:30 PM on Wednesday, February 12, 2020 in NBE's multipurpose gym and auditorium. Guests can come and go as schedules permit. All North Butler Elementary students and families are invited to attend.

post_text: This week, Mr. Black led his fourth grade students in multiplication boot camp. Short sessions of calisthenics exercises were integrated into a review of basic facts (and strategies for remembering them.) In the same way exercise shapes up muscles, heart, lungs, and bones, it also strengthens key areas of the brain, fuels the brain with oxygen and increases the number of connections between neurons. NBE staff are encouraged to find ways to integrate movement into the curriculum. Video from the session is available here: https://safesha.re/aw5

North Butler seniors Madison Klingenborg, Rainy Kock and Cassidy Staudt are seeking donations for the Allison Food Pantry as part of their 2019 National Honor Society Service Project. Although unknown to many, there are dozens of people around us each day that struggle with having enough food to eat. Any donation, regardless of how small or big, makes a difference in the lives of our neighbors. Boxes have been placed at the following places in Greene: NB High School, The Black Sheep Coffee Baa, LSB, and West Forty Market. Additionally, donation boxes can be found at the following places in Allison: NB Elementary, LSB, and J&Câ€™s Grocery. The drive will end Friday, December 20th. Thank you for all of your support in advance!

post_text:
The North Butler Schools Board of Education and administrative team would like to take a moment and wish everyone a Happy Holiday.

The good weather has allowed us to accumulate many hours of instruction so far. As a result of this and the change in our calendar from days to hours, we are able to offer our staff an additional day of professional learning on January 3rd. The extra day will help each building and the district meet their goals.

I would like to inform everyone that January 3rd will now become a professional development day for teachers and a non-school day for students. With the change in the calendar from days to hours, we have extra time built in. This means that students will not need to make up this time, and we will still meets the obligations that we have to the State.

We apologize for any inconveniences that this may cause, but this professional learning is vital to our future success as a staff.

Thank you for understanding.

Have a Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year!
